text: Luscious and jammy reds are medium-bodied, full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that combine ripe berry notes and pronounced jammy flavours. You can discern notes of cherry jam, wild berry jam or dark plum in these wines. Ripe tannins add the necessary structure for pairing the wines with food.
topNotch: Full-bodied, medium tannic, blackberry notes, blackcurrant notes, dark cherry notes
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Mellow and sweet whites are medium-dry or even sweet. You can discern apricot, honeydew melon and floral notes in these wines. Residual sugar rounds up the flavour.
topNotch: Medium sweet, medium acidic, honey melon notes, peach notes, hint of currant, flowery
tips: These wines are all characterised by delicious, fruity sweetness, which means that they are excellent for socialising and a good match for Eastern dishes and vegetables. Try with Indian vegetable or chicken korma, shrimp and cheese quiche or black label Emmental.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, fruity, citrus notes, green apple notes
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, berry notes, cherry notes, raspberry notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Medium dry, medium acidic, strawberry jam notes, light raspberry notes, slightly spicy
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Berried and fresh reds are light or medium-bodied wines infused with the flavours and acidity of fresh berries. You can discern ripe cranberry, raspberry and cherry notes in these wines. Crisp freshness makes them ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, ripe cranberry notes, blueberry notes, light vanilla notes
tips: Berried and fresh reds go well with pasta, vegetable and chicken dishes and internal organs, such as liver, but also with fish. Try with tomato-based pasta dishes, chicken stew with Moroccan spices or oven-baked salmon topped with blue cheese.

tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Nuanced and structured whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet wines with characteristically mineral and herbal flavours and aromas. You can also discern citrus, gooseberry and blackcurrant notes in these wines. Crisp acids add the necessary structure, making them an ideal accompaniment to food.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, currant notes, light lychee notes, citrus notes, tomato leaf notes, herbal notes
tips: Nuanced flavours combined with robust acidity make these wines an excellent match for fish and seafood dishes as well as slightly stronger flavours. Try with Finnish crayfish, clam dishes or blinis.

text: Mellow and sweet whites are medium-dry or even sweet. You can discern apricot, honeydew melon and floral notes in these wines. Residual sugar rounds up the flavour.
topNotch: Sweet, medium acidic, peach notes, lychee notes, honey melon notes, light rose notes
tips: These wines are all characterised by delicious, fruity sweetness, which means that they are excellent for socialising and a good match for Eastern dishes and vegetables. Try with Indian vegetable or chicken korma, shrimp and cheese quiche or black label Emmental.

text: Luscious and jammy reds are medium-bodied, full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that combine ripe berry notes and pronounced jammy flavours. You can discern notes of cherry jam, wild berry jam or dark plum in these wines. Ripe tannins add the necessary structure for pairing the wines with food.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, dark cherry notes, ripe cranberry notes, currant notes, spicy, light mocha notes
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Fruit wines and sparkling fruit wines are made from ingredients other than grapes. Aromatised wines are at least partially made from grapes, but berries or berry extract, or fruits or fruit extract, have been added to give flavour. Sparkling fruit wines often have currant, gooseberry and citrus flavours. In fruit wines, you can discern notes of apple, pear, blueberry, raspberry, cranberry or blackcurrant. Aromatised wines can be flavoured with strawberry, passion fruit, orange, raspberry, grapefruit or pear. The flavour is typically medium-sweet or sweet, and the wine can be fizzy or bubbly.
topNotch: Medium dry, acidic, citrus notes, raspberry notes, minerally
tips: Sparkling fruit wines, fruit wines and aromatised wines are perfect for socialising, as aperitifs or in mixed drinks and punches. Try them in cocktails or punches, and choose the berry or fruit that you like the most. You can adjust the alcohol content by adding spirits, liquor, sparkling water, tonic or juice. Decorate with the seasons berries, fruits and herbs.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, raspberry notes, wild strawberry notes, citrus notes, redcurrant notes, light flowery notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, berry notes, spicy, herbal notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Nuanced and structured whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet wines with characteristically mineral and herbal flavours and aromas. You can also discern citrus, gooseberry and blackcurrant notes in these wines. Crisp acids add the necessary structure, making them an ideal accompaniment to food.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, green apple notes, honey melon notes, citrus notes, light passion fruit notes, slightly flowery, minerally
tips: Nuanced flavours combined with robust acidity make these wines an excellent match for fish and seafood dishes as well as slightly stronger flavours. Try with Finnish crayfish, clam dishes or blinis.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, raspberry notes, redcurrant notes, hint of cherry, light spice notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Full-bodied, medium tannic, blackberry jam notes, cherry notes, light raspberry notes, dark chocolate notes, spicy
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, berry notes, currant notes, flowery

text: Specialities are beers that are rare or difficult to categorise into one of the generally used beer styles. The flavours range from crisp, refreshing mild beers to full-bodied, sweet and strong beers. There are both top- and bottom-fermented beers as well as spontaneously fermented beers.
topNotch: Yellowy brown, light-bodied, mildly hopped, fruity, citrus notes
tips: Some of the specialities are local traditional beers, and others are brand-new products. Examples of specialities are lambic, fruit beers, smoke beers, Trappist beers, flavoured beers, saison and sahti. Try a Trappist beer with black label Emmental, kriek (cherry beer) with brie, smoke beer with BBQ-seasoned skewers or sahti with sauna-smoked ham.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Medium dry, medium acidic, strawberry notes, cherry notes, citrus notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, ripe cranberry notes, light raspberry notes, gooseberry notes, hint of currant leaf
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, lemon notes, wild raspberry notes, peach notes, fresh, refreshing
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, cherry notes, blackberry notes, wild berry jam notes, light spice notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Luscious and jammy reds are medium-bodied, full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that combine ripe berry notes and pronounced jammy flavours. You can discern notes of cherry jam, wild berry jam or dark plum in these wines. Ripe tannins add the necessary structure for pairing the wines with food.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, cherry jam notes, blueberry notes, blackberry notes, light cocoa notes, slightly spicy
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, strawberry notes, raspberry notes, apple notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

topNotch: Full-bodied, medium tannic, blackberry jam notes, cherry notes, blueberry notes, chocolaty, light vanilla notes, hint of mocha
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Luscious and jammy reds are medium-bodied, full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that combine ripe berry notes and pronounced jammy flavours. You can discern notes of cherry jam, wild berry jam or dark plum in these wines. Ripe tannins add the necessary structure for pairing the wines with food.
topNotch: Full-bodied, medium tannic, cranberry jam notes, strawberry notes, light blackcurrant notes, spicy
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Medium dry, medium acidic, wild strawberry notes, raspberry notes, currant notes, hint of herb
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Nuanced and structured whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet wines with characteristically mineral and herbal flavours and aromas. You can also discern citrus, gooseberry and blackcurrant notes in these wines. Crisp acids add the necessary structure, making them an ideal accompaniment to food.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, green pear notes, whitecurrant notes, light grapefruit notes, herbal notes, hint of tomato leaves
tips: Nuanced flavours combined with robust acidity make these wines an excellent match for fish and seafood dishes as well as slightly stronger flavours. Try with Finnish crayfish, clam dishes or blinis.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, green pear notes, peach notes, light passion fruit notes, citrus notes, herbal notes
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, currant notes, apricot notes, peach notes, raspberry notes, slightly spicy
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Berried and fresh reds are light or medium-bodied wines infused with the flavours and acidity of fresh berries. You can discern ripe cranberry, raspberry and cherry notes in these wines. Crisp freshness makes them ideal for a variety of foods.

tips: Berried and fresh reds go well with pasta, vegetable and chicken dishes and internal organs, such as liver, but also with fish. Try with tomato-based pasta dishes, chicken stew with Moroccan spices or oven-baked salmon topped with blue cheese.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, dark cherry notes, boysenberry notes, chocolaty, slightly spicy
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, strawberry notes, apple notes, herbal notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, plum notes, blackberry notes, dark cherry notes
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Medium dry, acidic, apple notes, yellow plum notes, melon notes
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, low tannins, dark cherry notes, berry notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, raspberry notes, citrus notes, light strawberry notes, hint of redcurrant, spicy
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Fruit wines and sparkling fruit wines are made from ingredients other than grapes. Aromatised wines are at least partially made from grapes, but berries or berry extract, or fruits or fruit extract, have been added to give flavour. Sparkling fruit wines often have currant, gooseberry and citrus flavours. In fruit wines, you can discern notes of apple, pear, blueberry, raspberry, cranberry or blackcurrant. Aromatised wines can be flavoured with strawberry, passion fruit, orange, raspberry, grapefruit or pear. The flavour is typically medium-sweet or sweet, and the wine can be fizzy or bubbly.
topNotch: Sweet, medium acidic, rhubarb notes, wild strawberry notes, blood orange notes
tips: Sparkling fruit wines, fruit wines and aromatised wines are perfect for socialising, as aperitifs or in mixed drinks and punches. Try them in cocktails or punches, and choose the berry or fruit that you like the most. You can adjust the alcohol content by adding spirits, liquor, sparkling water, tonic or juice. Decorate with the seasons berries, fruits and herbs.

topNotch: Full-bodied, tannic, dark cherry notes, blackcurrant notes, hint of chocolate, hint of black pepper, oak notes
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, fruity, honey melon notes, herbal notes
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Specialities are beers that are rare or difficult to categorise into one of the generally used beer styles. The flavours range from crisp, refreshing mild beers to full-bodied, sweet and strong beers. There are both top- and bottom-fermented beers as well as spontaneously fermented beers.
topNotch: Yellowy brown, light-bodied, mildly hopped, citrus notes, fruity
tips: Some of the specialities are local traditional beers, and others are brand-new products. Examples of specialities are lambic, fruit beers, smoke beers, Trappist beers, flavoured beers, saison and sahti. Try a Trappist beer with black label Emmental, kriek (cherry beer) with brie, smoke beer with BBQ-seasoned skewers or sahti with sauna-smoked ham.

tips: These wines are all characterised by delicious, fruity sweetness, which means that they are excellent for socialising and a good match for Eastern dishes and vegetables. Try with Indian vegetable or chicken korma, shrimp and cheese quiche or black label Emmental.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, plum notes, blueberry jam notes, cherry notes, strawberry notes, spicy
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, redcurrant notes, raspberry notes, strawberry notes, cherry notes, hint of citrus
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Luscious and jammy reds are medium-bodied, full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that combine ripe berry notes and pronounced jammy flavours. You can discern notes of cherry jam, wild berry jam or dark plum in these wines. Ripe tannins add the necessary structure for pairing the wines with food.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, berry notes, dark cherry notes, herbal notes
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, dark cherry notes, plum notes, chocolaty, mocha notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Generous and toasty whites are mouth-filling wines that are dry or medium-dry. You can discern notes of yellow plum, spices and toasted oak in these wines. The rich finish is exceptionally long.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, peach notes, honey melon notes, light vanilla notes, oak notes
tips: The rich, full-bodied character is combined with toasted notes or oakiness, and the wines are a great match not only for oily fish but also for chicken, turkey and even game bird and pork dishes. Try with flamed salmon, smoked duck or creamy mushroom soup.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, red berry notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.

tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, medium-dry, cherry jam notes, wild berry notes, spicy, light vanilla notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Nuanced and developed reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines in which maturation has created notes of leather, stable, oak and herbs. These earthy flavours and aromas become more pronounced as the wine matures and develops. Oak maturation also adds spicy and vanilla notes.
topNotch: Full-bodied, medium tannic, sour cherry, cranberry notes, fig notes, woody
tips: Nuanced and developed wines go well will rustic meat dishes. You can also pair them with cheese or enjoy them on their own. Try with reindeer steak, entrecôte or hard, aged cheeses, such as Gouda, Parmesan or Manchego.

MORE INFORMATION: Not available in the online store. The product requires an unbroken cold chain.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION: May contain sediment. Small artisan brewery
text: Specialities are beers that are rare or difficult to categorise into one of the generally used beer styles. The flavours range from crisp, refreshing mild beers to full-bodied, sweet and strong beers. There are both top- and bottom-fermented beers as well as spontaneously fermented beers.
topNotch: Cinnamon-brown, extra full-bodied, cloudy, mildly hopped, toasted malt notes, grainy notes, aromatic
tips: Some of the specialities are local traditional beers, and others are brand-new products. Examples of specialities are lambic, fruit beers, smoke beers, Trappist beers, flavoured beers, saison and sahti. Try a Trappist beer with black label Emmental, kriek (cherry beer) with brie, smoke beer with BBQ-seasoned skewers or sahti with sauna-smoked ham.

tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Luscious and jammy reds are medium-bodied, full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that combine ripe berry notes and pronounced jammy flavours. You can discern notes of cherry jam, wild berry jam or dark plum in these wines. Ripe tannins add the necessary structure for pairing the wines with food.

tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, raspberry notes, citrus notes, light wild strawberry notes, hint of blueberry
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

text: Nuanced and structured whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet wines with characteristically mineral and herbal flavours and aromas. You can also discern citrus, gooseberry and blackcurrant notes in these wines. Crisp acids add the necessary structure, making them an ideal accompaniment to food.
topNotch: Dry, very acidic, green apple notes, lime notes, currant leaf notes, light herb notes, hint of mineral
tips: Nuanced flavours combined with robust acidity make these wines an excellent match for fish and seafood dishes as well as slightly stronger flavours. Try with Finnish crayfish, clam dishes or blinis.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, low tannins, cherry notes, flowery, berry notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.

text: Nuanced and developed reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines in which maturation has created notes of leather, stable, oak and herbs. These earthy flavours and aromas become more pronounced as the wine matures and develops. Oak maturation also adds spicy and vanilla notes.

topNotch: Full-bodied, medium tannic, cherry notes, raspberry notes, plum notes, spicy, light vanilla notes, hint of paprika
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, citrus notes, green apple notes, minerally
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Mellow and sweet whites are medium-dry or even sweet. You can discern apricot, honeydew melon and floral notes in these wines. Residual sugar rounds up the flavour.
topNotch: Medium sweet, medium acidic, peach notes, pineapple notes, light citrus notes, slightly flowery
tips: These wines are all characterised by delicious, fruity sweetness, which means that they are excellent for socialising and a good match for Eastern dishes and vegetables. Try with Indian vegetable or chicken korma, shrimp and cheese quiche or black label Emmental.

text: Robust and powerful reds are full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that have rich flavours. Due to oak maturation, you can discern powerful spicy notes. High tannins lend these wines a good structure.
topNotch: Full-bodied, tannic, currant notes, dark cherry notes, blueberry notes, black pepper notes, light mocha notes, warm
tips: Due to their tannins, these wines are a good match for equally robust foods, such as game and other hearty meat dishes or strong cheeses.Try with venison or rabbit stew, herb-marinated lamb chops or strong cheeses, such as aged Gruyère or Roquefort.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, medium-sweet, blueberry jam notes, ripe blackcurrant notes, light medicinal herb notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Fruit wines and sparkling fruit wines are made from ingredients other than grapes. Aromatised wines are at least partially made from grapes, but berries or berry extract, or fruits or fruit extract, have been added to give flavour. Sparkling fruit wines often have currant, gooseberry and citrus flavours. In fruit wines, you can discern notes of apple, pear, blueberry, raspberry, cranberry or blackcurrant. Aromatised wines can be flavoured with strawberry, passion fruit, orange, raspberry, grapefruit or pear. The flavour is typically medium-sweet or sweet, and the wine can be fizzy or bubbly.
topNotch: Sweet, low tannins, raspberry notes, cherry notes, orangey, light cinnamon notes, fresh, refreshing
tips: Sparkling fruit wines, fruit wines and aromatised wines are perfect for socialising, as aperitifs or in mixed drinks and punches. Try them in cocktails or punches, and choose the berry or fruit that you like the most. You can adjust the alcohol content by adding spirits, liquor, sparkling water, tonic or juice. Decorate with the seasons berries, fruits and herbs.

Decorate with the seasons berries, fruits and herbs.

text: Nuanced and structured whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet wines with characteristically mineral and herbal flavours and aromas. You can also discern citrus, gooseberry and blackcurrant notes in these wines. Crisp acids add the necessary structure, making them an ideal accompaniment to food.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, passion fruit notes, mango notes, currant notes, nettle notes
tips: Nuanced flavours combined with robust acidity make these wines an excellent match for fish and seafood dishes as well as slightly stronger flavours. Try with Finnish crayfish, clam dishes or blinis.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, citrus notes, nectarine notes, pear notes, light herb notes, flowery
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Smooth and fruity reds are medium-bodied or full-bodied wines that often have a trace of sweetness. Soft fruitiness is a typical characteristic of these wines. You can discern notes of ripe or dried fruits and delicate spiciness in these wines. With low or medium tannins, they are also suitable for those with a sensitive mouth.
topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, medium-dry, blueberry jam notes, cranberry notes, toffee notes, vanilla notes, spicy
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Mellow and sweet whites are medium-dry or even sweet. You can discern apricot, honeydew melon and floral notes in these wines. Residual sugar rounds up the flavour.
topNotch: Medium dry, medium acidic, ripe citrus notes, honey melon notes, light flowery notes, herbal notes
tips: These wines are all characterised by delicious, fruity sweetness, which means that they are excellent for socialising and a good match for Eastern dishes and vegetables. Try with Indian vegetable or chicken korma, shrimp and cheese quiche or black label Emmental.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, redcurrant notes, light strawberry notes, hint of herb
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

topNotch: Medium-bodied, medium tannic, strawberry notes, raspberry notes, milk chocolate notes, herbal notes
tips: These versatile players of the red wine world are ideal for socialising and buffet tables. Try with sweet-and-sour pork stew, Thai chicken curry or spicy sausages, such as chorizo or salami.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, acidic, ripe citrus notes, honey melon notes, apricot notes, green apple notes, flowery
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Robust and powerful reds are full-bodied or very full-bodied wines that have rich flavours. Due to oak maturation, you can discern powerful spicy notes. High tannins lend these wines a good structure.
topNotch: Full-bodied, tannic, dark cherry notes, plum notes, currant notes, mocha notes, spicy, rich oak notes
tips: Due to their tannins, these wines are a good match for equally robust foods, such as game and other hearty meat dishes or strong cheeses.Try with venison or rabbit stew, herb-marinated lamb chops or strong cheeses, such as aged Gruyère or Roquefort.

text: Rosé wines are usually made from red grapes, and they obtain their colour from a short contact with grape skins. Some New World rosés are made by adding a little red wine to white wine. The level of sweetness ranges from dry to sweet and the flavour from mineral and herbal to strong berry notes. The lightest rosés are pale pink and the darkest translucent red. You can discern redcurrant, strawberry and raspberry notes in these wines.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, raspberry notes, citrus notes, strawberry notes
tips: Rosé wines are ideal for socialising, and you can also pair them with food. Rosés are a good choice for summer buffets with cold foods, such as cold cuts, salads and shellfish. You can also try rosé with rustic salads, grilled drumsticks or bouillabaisse.

topNotch: Medium-bodied, tannic, redcurrant notes, cherry notes, light paprika notes, herbal notes
tips: Wines with rich flavours and aromas are a good choice when serving meat dishes. Try with BBQ-marinated pork ribs, beef and vegetable skewers or T bone steaks.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Medium sweet, acidic, pineapple notes, citrus marmalade notes, honey melon notes, green apple notes
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.

text: Smooth and light whites are dry wines whose ripe fruitiness is accompanied by delicate acidity. You can discern pear, apple and peach notes in these wines. Due to their smoothness, they are also suitable for those who do not normally like dry white wine.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, apple notes, ripe citrus notes, light yellow plum notes, spicy
tips: These wines are light, versatile and well suited to socialising and buffet tables or as an accompaniment to vegetables. Try with chanterelle tart, vegetable tapas or tuna pasta.

text: Crisp and fruity whites are dry, medium-dry or medium-sweet. They are typically crisply acidic, which balances their rich fruitiness. You can discern yellow plum, apple and peach notes in these wines. Crisp acids create a fresh finish, making these wines ideal for a variety of foods.
topNotch: Dry, medium acidic, pineapple notes, citrus notes, apricot notes
tips: These wines are an excellent match for savoury starters, pasta and fish and seafood dishes. Try with different kinds of tapas or antipasti, shrimp salad or sushi.
